JW: there are parallel efforts to build databases across scales & systems (species, traits, genes, climates). How do we synthesize? #ESA2016
JW: @neotomadb is a boundary organization, creating conversations among data contributors, informaticians and end users. #ESA2016
JW: check out COPDESS, a registry for domain-specific repositories for publishers. #ESA2016
Williams gives a shout-out to @neotomadb, a spatio-temporal archive of species occurrence and abundance data from paleorecords. #ESA2016
JW: Just as there are many paleo-scientists across fields, there are many methods. Integrating all this data requires informatics. #ESA2016
JW: Community Level Models outperform Species Distribution Models during periods of novel climates. #ESA2016
JW: Coukd Holocene trees keep pace with postglacial climate change? Biotic velocities matched--or exceeded--climate velocities! #ESA2016
JW: We can pick up abrupt, dramatic changes in vegetation on the order of a decade or less in the paleo record. #ESA2016
JW: Large-scale syntheses are powerful, but we can still learn a tremendous amount from studying the changes at single sites! #ESA2016
JW: The rate & magnitude of deglacial climate change was similar to today, though human influences were obviously less than today. #ESA2016
JW: The global changes of the last deglaciation drove ecological changes, including species range shifts and novel ecosystems. #ESA2016
JW: Paleoclimatologists have been especially good at identifying earth system feedbacks, which have mostly  been physical. #ESA2016
JW: The last deglaciation in N. America was the last great global change: abrupt climate change, extinctions, human arrival. #ESA2016
JW: Macro-scale ecology requires collaboration among statisticians, modelers, informatics, and field and lab ecologists. #ESA2016
